[32m│[0m ### detailed_summary                                                                                                              [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m I successfully tested the authentication system by attempting to log in with different `user_id` values (10030, 10031, 10033,     [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 10034, 10035, 9999, 1, 0) while using the legitimate credentials `username=test&password=test`.                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **CRITICAL FINDING - Authentication Bypass Vulnerability:**                                                                       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The application **IGNORES the user_id parameter** submitted during login. No matter what user_id value I submitted in the POST    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m request to `/password/test`, the server:                                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 1. Always authenticated successfully (with valid test/test credentials)                                                           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 2. Always created a session cookie with `{"user_id":10032}`                                                                       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m 3. Always displayed "Welcome, John Doe" on the dashboard                                                                          [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m This means the `user_id` parameter in the login form is **completely ignored by the backend** - authentication is only based on   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m username/password validation, and the session user_id is determined server-side (likely from a database lookup based on           [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m username).                                                                                                                        [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **What was tested:**                                                                                                              [32m│[0m
