[32m│[0m                                                                                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m **Conclusion:**                                                                                                                   [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m The user_id parameter in the login form is a **client-side only value** that has no effect on authentication. The backend         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m properly validates credentials and sets the user_id based on the username lookup, making it **not exploitable for user            [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m impersonation**. This is actually the **correct and secure behavior** - client-submitted user_id values should never be trusted.  [32m│[0m
